  <description type="morphology">Shrubs, 10–30 dm. Short-shoot leaf blades 2–3.5 cm, not usually drying dark. Inflorescences often pilose. Flowers 12 mm diam.; styles 3–5.</description>
  <description type="phenology">Flowering Apr; fruiting Sep–Oct.</description>
  <description type="habitat">Habitat not recorded, probably brush;</description>
  <description type="elevation">10–200 m;</description>
  <description type="distribution">Ala., Ga., Miss., Tenn.</description>
  <discussion>Variety mohrii is recorded with certainty only east of the Mississippi River; it is perhaps very rare. In the co-type, Beadle 236A, the inflorescences may be glabrous or pilose The relatively small, short leaves, small flowers, 3–5 styles, and broadly elliptic to suborbiculate extension-shoot leaves clearly mark var. mohrii as a member of the reverchonii group. Variety mohrii is notable for its strongly and sharply serrate leaf margins.</discussion>
